text: La la Land is just amazing. It cured my insomnia and sent me to la la land literally within minutes. But why?  1. Plot. Nobody watches a musical movie for its plot. But it is unforgivable to conjure up a clear oscar bait with a plot skimpier than Kim K's g-string and as formulaic and unimaginative as Trump's combover.  2. Music. You can forgive the plot but can you forgive the music since it's a musical movie? None of the tunes is memorable and the score is inferior to even that of Nocturnal Animals' (music is not even its key selling point).  3. The singing. Where do you even begin? We know that both leads are not known for their singing or musical talents but Ryan Gosling's singing can only be described as Kermit warbling in pain when Miss Piggy is not available for the night. At best.  4. The casting. Gosling clearly looks very uncomfortable throughout the movie and within 20 mins you get a clear sense that he's not even committed or even bothered and he just wishes this nightmare to be over. And Stone? With her resting bitch face (RBF) she would be effective in roles such as the scene-stealing one in Birdman. But as a delusional, campy, act-cute, wide-eyed girl next door with a RBF? Give me a break!!  5. Lack of chemistry between the co-stars. Let's just say that there's more sexual chemistry if you put Trump and Hillary in the same room. On the same token, it's also more believable for Obama to hump Kim Jong Un than for the leads to get it on.  6. Dialogue. The script seems to be written by a pre-school kid with mild retardation or a drooling Kanye upon receiving a full mental exorcism la A Clockwork Orange.  7. Pacing. I snored. The lady to my left snored. The Uncle behind me snored. Within 20 minutes.  8. Mandatory conflict scene. It's as intense as a spoilt child having an existential crisis over the fact that he was fed more yellow peas than green peas.  9. Ending. Unique and clever and surprising? Nope. Just lazy and manipulative and pretentious plagiarised hogwash.

text: I've seen "La La Land" and let me tell you...it was original. It was gorgeously fun musical experience I had ever seen. And for all these years that every single musical film tried so hard to have a fun time, but this one it glows me a lot. These two performances were fantastic and they sure have a lot of fun for their life going experience of what they really want for their own dreams. The songs were dazzling and boy, hearing these songs that you can't get out of your head. Yay, take that "Frozen" with "Let It Go" song which people think is cool, but here I can remember them as I can tune my jazzy songs while hearing them in my iPhone. The dance scenes were fun, the real sequences were beautiful and so colorful, and it was an amazing musical film. Like most of the audience since musical films didn't have much potential, but you're watching a fun musical experience. I can't believe this movie it's a huge hit from critically acclaimed people and I'm one of them that no matter what it's a movie classic for the next future. Go check it out people, it was beautiful. One of the best 2016 and I'm not going to say this, but it's easily on my top 10 favorite films that this one deserves it.  [100] üëçüëç ‚≠ê

text: I'm going to be the buzzkill here.  I'm not somebody who falls for hype of any kind when it comes to movies and I think too many are oversold as "best film of the year."  I saw La La Land the other day and was disappointed, quite frankly.  The songs aren't memorable and if you subtract the novelty of these two movie stars singing and dancing you basically have your standard boy-meets-girl movie.  It was inconsistent and I was bored in a couple of places.  And I HATED the ending - I found it depressing.  The upside - Emma Stone's acting was great and Gosling's piano playing was remarkable.  There's much to like about the film but much to dislike as well.

text: LA LA LAND is a TRANSCENDENT, heartwarming & poetic movie that truly seems to be taken directly from a dream. A movie full of SURPISES that combines the prefect proportion of comedy, romance, drama, with some incredibly raw & moving performances. LA LA LAND also displays a very unique film production style, breath-taking sceneries and an over-abundance of amazing talents. Every song transports you to new places, every dance makes you want to dream and every scene leaves you full of WONDER & MAGIC.  In my opinion, saying that this movie is "Good" would be an understatement, this movie is indeed an outstanding nerve-wrecking and emotional MASTERPIECE. One of the rare movies that brought tears to my eyes and overwhelmed me with an intense and constant overflow of feelings. This movie erased the clear distinction between emotions, leaving you speechless and full of uncertainties. INSPIRING! I highly recommend this movie as one of the best movie that anyone could watch to perfectly start the new year.

text: I have said there can be a film with an unoriginal story, but can be made enjoyable with a fresh approach. I don't feel La La Land did that.   The tunes were unmemerable. If I do think of the score/songs, I'm trying to actually remember them than already humming it. However, City of Stars was quite good. Perhaps a bit over-used, and the first introduction on the pier felt odd and out-of-place. Like, where did it come from suddenly in this film after the previous scene(s)? Same can be said for all other songs, which really are not many at all.   It's a nice romantic drama film to watch and nice to see both actors together and as their characters. They are quite loveable and cute together. However it was another unoriginal story of struggling actress and musician meet and fall in love and follow dreams together, either ending up successful together or alone. Luckily, their chemistry and warm scenes together make it watchable and not overly distracting.  Maybe the point of the film relates to it's own characters. Trying to be a revolutionist instead of traditionalist. Maybe "La La Land" is trying to be revolutionary and fresh instead of a traditional musical by simply being a romantic drama featuring musical numbers - doing something new than straight-forward and a checklist. But even then, with a part satire and realism of the Los Angeles world, including traffic and constant sun and warmth (that film funnily needed to show time pacing by listing the seasons) it still doesn't come across as anything groundbreaking.

text: Well what a clever and interesting film. The evolution of the musical from Bessie Love and Broadway Melody through to present day and a promising look to the future thankfully avoiding the cliche of "Glee". Paying homage on the way to the masterly Gene Kelly films of the 40's. Twixt all this recognition of its adolescence fruition it tells a modern romantic tale believable and fraught with twists worthy of West Side story and indeed Romeo and Juliet. I can understand the universal acclaim but it seemed to me very much a film makers film and therefore valued by those who value the Art. Not the best film ever but if this is the future of the musical then play on.

text: SPOILER ALERT!!!!!!!!!!!!! . . . . . . . . . .    My broken heart is going to take a long time to heal.  They did this with Brokeback Mountain, Prime, Titanic, Me before You, The Best of Me, Casablanca, Atonement, Becoming Jane, Gone with the Wind, Blue Jay. How many more heartbreaking romance movies have to exist????? In this horrible world we live in (not always horrible, ofc), we already have so much negative stuff happening in the world. Watching a beautiful romance movie with a non-heartbreaking, happy ending where they end up together would allow us all to leave this violent, hateful world temporarily to enjoy this beautiful fictional world. WHY WOULD YOU END IT LIKE THAT??? JUST GIVE US THE CLICHES, idc how annoying and stereotypical it is. I understand this movie was making fun of cliches in Hollywood romance movies how all of them have happy endings, but SO WHAT. Couldn't they have been ironic in making fun of that notion by MAKING it a cliche ending? SO many real life romance stories end well and the couple stays together/stay married for 60 years!! It's not THAT uncommon!

text: La la Land is just amazing. It cured my insomnia and sent me to la la land literally within minutes. But why?  1. Plot. Nobody watches a musical movie for its plot. But it is unforgivable to conjure up a clear oscar bait with a plot skimpier than Kim K's g-string and as formulaic and unimaginative as Trump's combover.  2. Music. You can forgive the plot but can you forgive the music since it's a musical movie? None of the tunes is memorable and the score is inferior to even that produced by an amateur funeral band.  3. The singing. Where do you even begin? We know that both leads are not known for their singing or musical talents but Ryan Gosling's singing can only be described as Kermit warbling in pain when Miss Piggy is not available for the night. At best.  4. The casting. Gosling clearly looks very uncomfortable throughout the movie and within 20 mins you get a clear sense that he's not even committed or even bothered and he just wishes this nightmare to be over. And Stone? With her resting bitch face (RBF) she would be effective in roles such as the scene-stealing one in Birdman. But as a delusional, campy, act-cute, wide-eyed girl next door with a RBF? Give me a break!! You know something is seriously wrong when John Legend with limited scenes is your best actor.  5. Lack of chemistry between the co-stars. Let's just say that there's more sexual chemistry if you put Trump and Hillary in the same room. On the same token, it's also more believable for Obama to hump Kim Jong Un than for the leads to get it on.  6. Dialogue. The script seems to be written by a pre-school kid with mild retardation or a drooling Kanye upon receiving a full mental exorcism la A Clockwork Orange.  7. Pacing. I snored. The lady to my left snored. The uncle behind me snored. Within 20 minutes. Doesn't help that most scenes are almost akin to that created by a Z grade producer of a third world tourism promotional teaser.  8. Mandatory conflict scene. It's as intense as a spoilt child having an existential crisis over the fact that he was fed more yellow peas than green peas.  9. Magical mysticism scene. Ordinarily it would look funny, playful or creative. Here it just looks juvenile, awkward and clumsy.  10. Ending. Unique and clever and surprising? Nope. Just lazy, manipulative, pretentious and plagiarised hogwash.

text: This movie is such a work of art üòç The creativity in this is at maximum from the acting to the notes that would pass through your ears. It gives that feeling of nostalgia, yet it sets a spark of something new. I honestly was watching the movie with a heavy heart solely because of it, and I was shocked to see a 50's style format from such a movie within this period of time! The romanticism of aspirations and dreams caught my attention the best, being both a dreamer and a hopeless romantic. Also, the casting made it even more comfortable for the plot. This is, I think, the third time Emma Stone and Ryan Gosling are paired together in a movie, and that made things easier for me to picture as if everything was merely a memory of some sort. With the colorful sights of LA and the stories of two dreamers clashing into each other, I think this is the best movie for me so far within this year.

text: I saw the movie today. And I think it was interesting. On one end it paid tribute to the MGM musicals with some of the director shots and that captivating ending (Through the fury camera shots I instantly thought of that 18 minute fantasy break in "American In Paris". But their neat trick is that they used REAL LIFE MOMENTS. Excellent.) I appreciated that aspect of it, as well as the plot, which detailed a unique covenant exchange.  The only negative I have is, while I loved the chemistry between Emma Stone and Ryan Gosling, I wished for more from them in terms of song and dance. If you work with them 3-6 months longer than they might have, you have dance routines akin to Rogers and Astaire. (I felt the choreography was not tight enough) But that's me 1) wanting perfection or 2) actually "holding on to tradition as opposed to moving into the future." - get it?  Overall, the movie was inspiring, as it effortlessly blended a drama-meets-romance plot with musical.  It deserved the many Oscar nominations it received because of its imagery and originality and it was one of the best movies I've seen this year.

text: Overrated, Over-hyped and trying too much to make an impact. It's a chick flick intended for Ryan Gosling fans and soap opera lovers. The achievement is maybe more on the "Artistic" side, not on the narrative side. The story progresses very slowly, and I kept asking myself - what did the director was trying to say...  And that is ok, just please don't compare it to classics like star wars or more appropriately - Musicals like "Hair" which is a master piece on its own rights. 14 Oscar nominees ?! hard to believe. I did like the two main actors - they played pretty good, but this movie has to decide what it is... a musical, a romantic film, a get-after-your-dreams movie, an artistic feat  ? I honestly couldn't tell.

text: Praise   A subconscious and unspoken stigma and stereotype exists among movie producers and most people that a film is for children if it is all about bright colors, simple messages of happiness and verbally expressed joy through song and beautiful art as well as principles of familiar real life things that most good people hold as ideals such as young love or honor in various jobs. Somehow La La Land proves this utterly wrong and rips those biases utterly to shreds. It reminds us all that color and life and goodness is what we are looking to see in real entertainment, which is a childlike feature in all of us, the innocence we long for. It‚Äôs balance between serious themes and dreamy heart make it irresistibly attractive and intriguing. It proved that old fashioned values combined with art in simple and pleasant forms, as applied to art, are every bit as meaningful and held as respectful to a huge adult audience by the 340 million it‚Äôs already made. Obviously, it was made after the way of an older and ‚Äúbygone era‚Äù of films that were classier, more innocent, more simple, more musical, and more jolly. But I believe it made a masterpiece of itself accidentally, perhaps because the more youthful producers fill in their absence of true experience with a bygone genre (the 1920s, 30s, 40s, and 50s) with their imaginations, that give their forbears the benefit of the doubt in the way of true quality and meaning, but, who cares? It worked! This film was a masterpiece among films in my opinion. It proved to me something I have long believed to the center, which is that part of the glory of being human is to embrace innocence, and the purer elements of art such as mastery of pictures, singing, presentations, and dance with honed practice by experienced and passionate artists‚Ä¶of a kind. La La Land proved to be more than paying homage or milking nostalgia to some supposedly greater and forgotten era, but a solid and deliciously indestructible piece of living proof that new and original pieces of entertainment not only can be made but can make today‚Äôs world brighter and more beautiful by remaining optimistic, original, and true to form in the process! This movie is gold! It could hold the potential for some kind of modern renaissance of worthwhile art in many forms. It didn‚Äôt make me long for the past, it didn‚Äôt break my heart, but it didn‚Äôt let me away easy either, it didn‚Äôt leave me critical, it didn‚Äôt leave me without a smile on my face, it didn‚Äôt leave me content, but it didn‚Äôt leave me unsatisfied, it gave me just that right balance of entertainment to not only pleasantly distract me away from the woes of real life but want to get back to it and make something more of it, and that is meaning! It left me wanting more true art in other forms, and if a movie can pull at my inner humanity like that, it‚Äôs masterful enough to be called an original masterpiece, if there ever was one. Like other great movies like Star Wars, somehow it just hit the spot with the perfect balance of just the right things; drama, color, comedy, originality, simplicity, easiness of understanding, heart, a touch of fantasy, a touch of realism, plenty of romance, seriousness, a little sadness, small aspects of uniqueness, and not overdone in any of those qualities. For this reason it should stand the test of time. What a wonderful film. I standards have been raised.  Five out of Five stars. -¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Sam Tomlinson¬†¬†¬†¬† - 2/23/17

text: The backlash for this movie is nonsense.  The liberals and SJWs have fucking ruined it with the silly complaints that La La Land never committed.  The movie is not racist in anyway, you're only making it racist by the way you are thinking.  You are the problem, not it.  This movie in my eyes is a complete masterpiece.  Sure, I can list some plot holes that don't make sense in the narrative, but with every movie comes problems.  While I think this movie is better than Moonlight, I am happy Moonlight won instead of this.  The movie already had its success and doesn't need anymore awards or money.  It made more than enough with 300 million worldwide, a bunch of nominations, and wins from other awards during its run.  It doesn't need the best picture win more than Moonlight does.  I am glad the Academy decided to split up the awards.  Moonlight can have best picture, while Damien Chazelle rightfully deserves best director.

text: I give two squats about the Oscars or if this should have gotten an award or not.  I saw this last Friday and decided to check out the trailer for Moonlight. LA LA Land is a fun movie. I'm sure moonlight is probably good and I will likely watch it next. I currently just want something fun. Every movie doesn't have to expose me to some struggle or show me it can be "darker" than the last rendition(Lego Batman even made fun of that trend).  Here is what I took from the movie: If you have a lot of experience with old movies, this one will get your memory going as you'll swear you've seen this scene before.  LA LA land hocks from a lot of old movies. Fred Astair, Danny Kay, Bing Crosby,Debbie Reynolds, Rosemary Clooney, etc. There are a lot of little subtle nods. The main actors even dressed in a similar style.   Don't see it like it will be nonstop singing(Avita, Les Miserables ,Sweeny Todd), nor like Seven Brides for Seven Brothers.  Maybe a little closer to Singing in the Rain, for song and dance. I wouldn't have minded just a little more dance. Take your wife, take your girlfriend (not at the same time) and just smile.

text: Here's a philosophical thought driven by this movie's ending (spoilers ahead) on the nature of storytelling:  Why didn't their relationship work out in the end?  "Because that's the way the film was written," you say.  Why was the film written that way?  "Uh..."  I'll tell you why. Damien Chazelle chose that ending because he didn't want your usual "happily ever after" clich√©. He wanted to do something more original. "Paper Towns" by John Green is another example of this kind of ending.   But in a story, no part of it (especially the ending/climax) should be chosen for what it is NOT. It should be chosen for what it is. And I see no way this story is made better by that ending, outside of the avoidance of a clich√©.

text: Well don't get me wrong this is a fine little musical with nice dancing and colors - gotta love that freeway scene...especially if you've ever lived in L.A. I'm thinking this is where all the raves came from about the opening scene, people who actually live in Los Angeles...but then I got to thinking, could I have even sat through this film if I didn't already know and love LA? It's a musical like the Wedding Singer is a musical. Don't get me wrong I loved the Wedding Singer as a teen, but that's about what this amounts to...actually in a way it's worse because it revealed to me that apparently the old white men of the Academy are not only old and white and male, but so brittle and narcissistic that apparently even the struggling actress and underemployed pianist had to be made unrealistically wealthy for this to be a "happy" film...I got a news flash for anyone living in Arkansas: if you come to L.A. to look for an acting or music career, you will be living in a house built in the 1930s divided into four rooms which you will share with 15 people, and you will take public transportation. text: Lots of people dislike this move because the ending supposedly and apparently ‚Äúsucks‚Äù, but you have to admit, the music and soundtrack to this film is amazing and well-done. Emma Stone and Ryan Gosling‚Äôs phenomenal acting performances really made us think and look deeper into Mia and Sebastian‚Äôs characters, and really put us in their shoes. The movie to me, was as sweet as apple pie, and warm as molten chocolate lava fudge. Especially the ending.  The ending was not what a lot of people expected, but if they were to look at the lessons that it teaches, isn‚Äôt that the whole point of the ending? The point of life?¬†You encounter something so amazing that you‚Äôd want it for the rest of your life, but you also have to give up another amazing thing to get the new one. You meet someone that instantly lights up your world, and you‚Äôd want and need them in your life, but you can‚Äôt, because your heart tells you that you have to pursue your career that you so longed worked for and respected. You end up facing some difficult choices. Life is like that, and it‚Äôs not always gonna be fair. It‚Äôs not always happy-ever-after. There are paths in life that will force you to make a decision, and sometimes you‚Äôll doubt if you made the right decision. But that‚Äôs life. Not everything will always be your way. The important thing is as long as you listen to your heart. Cherish the experience you have: show love and respect to all those around you, and make meaningful memories with the ones you love. Maybe sometimes, it‚Äôll work, maybe sometimes it won‚Äôt. Be patient and persevere; when one door closes, another one opens, and you just have to make your own choices in life. And maybe one day, you‚Äôll look back and cherish the memories you have made, the paths you have taken, and the lessons you learned through your experiences. Life isn‚Äôt fair, and it‚Äôs not supposed to be; and not everything is a happy-ever-after. But it‚Äôs all part of the experience, and one day you will look back at these days, at all this pain, and you will cherish it forever. It‚Äôs the decisions that we make today that count and shape our lives, and whether or not we also listened to our heart. Life isn‚Äôt fair, and you won‚Äôt always get the happy ending; but as long as you listen to your heart, and cherish and love those around you, who knows what miracle could drop by your house. You will one day look back, and cherish all the memorable memories you have made in your experiences.

text: My intepreation of the film: before Mia and Sebastian met each other, they had their own dreams, which they were chasing. Mia thought her biggest dream was to become an actress and Sebastian thought his biggest dream was to save jazz by opening his own jazz club. but then they met each other and fell in love. It was then where they realized, that the actual dream had always been a quite different one: to find true love. And they did find it in each other. Notice also when "city of stars " was played the first time in the movie, it was right after Sebastian had told mia about his "dream" in the jazz club. But when he sang the line "is this the start of something wonderful, or one more dream, that i cannot make true" .. he was actually singing about the dream to find the true love with mia (he kind of felt, she was the right one just by then), but he was afraid to not being able to make this dream come true, because by that time, Mia was still together with this other Guy Greg. Also when "City of stars" is played in full lenght later, the lyrics lead to this idea as well. In the last scene of La La Land, when they both have the "flashback" of how things should have been going, they both realized, they had given up the real dream: true love. And instead they had followed their other dreams, which is also good, but still the "true dream" had always been a different one...

text: Okay, so this movie. Wow. Just, wow. I love it more than I love anything else in the world. Seriously, I own the vinyl of the score, I have posters of it on my wall, I have seen the movie god knows how many times and my love for this movie will never stop growing. I  even found the overture to the movie (which is very beautiful, I might add). However, there is something very odd about this trailer. At 1:47 the three roommates are dancing next to a garden. That's not in the movie, and don't tell me it's in the song "Someone in the Crowd", because I have seen and studied this film enough to realize that it is not. My guess is that part of the song was cut from the film after the trailer was released, but before the movie came out. If you know where in the movie this scene is, I would love to know.

text: the ending made me so upset and i‚Äôm still not over it but that‚Äôs what made it such a great movie‚Äîit didn‚Äôt have the perfect happy ending you‚Äôd expect out of a movie with two people in love. they both achieved their fine arts dreams and they couldn‚Äôt have done it without the help of one another. there relationship was limiting their ability to pursue their own dreams, and they knew they couldn‚Äôt be together forever. they both even said  ‚Äúi‚Äôll always love you‚Äù when mia had her big audition towards the end of the movie. and they will. the epilogue scene is flawless, but it got me in my tears. the very end when mia was leaving the club but turned around to look at sebastian one last time was so pure and a good conclusion, especially when their theme started playing subtly on flute, it was so perfect and delicate. i‚Äôm tearing up as i type this. likewise, the sound track is incredible, especially since it‚Äôs all original songs written for the movie. being a flutist in a symphony and a saxophonist in a jazz band, it fit perfectly‚Äîthe jazz arrangements (like City of Stars) and the orchestral arrangements (like Planetarium) were so beautiful crafted and i listen to them everyday. must i mention that emma stone and ryan gosling had amazing chemistry throughout the movie and i loved them together, i‚Äôm glad it was emma stone rather than emma watson who had the role of mia. emma stone is beautiful and played her role perfectly. she‚Äôll always be one of my favorite actresses.
